---
layout: layout-base.njk
title: Frost Dates by City | GrowByDate
description: Look up average last spring frost, first fall frost, and frost-free growing season length by city.
canonical: "https://growbydate.com/data/frost-dates-by-city/"
---

<section class="card leaderboardHero">
  <p class="eyebrow">Reference table</p>
  <h1>Frost Dates by City</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Look up average last spring frost, first fall frost, and frost-free season length by city.
    These dates help you estimate when tender crops can usually go outside in spring and how much outdoor growing time remains before fall frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="leaderboardStatGrid" aria-label="Frost date data summary">
  <article class="leaderboardStat">
    <span class="statLabel">Cities listed</span>
    <strong>{{ frostDateReference.totalReferenceCities }}</strong>
    <span class="small">Published city records with frost-date reference values.</span>
  </article>
  <article class="leaderboardStat">
    <span class="statLabel">Median frost-free season</span>
    <strong>{{ frostDateReference.medianFrostFreeDays }} days</strong>
    <span class="small">Median across the current city list.</span>
  </article>
  <article class="leaderboardStat">
    <span class="statLabel">Use this for</span>
    <strong>Planting windows</strong>
    <span class="small">Seed starting, transplant timing, and fall harvest planning.</span>
  </article>
</section>

<section class="card leaderboardTableWrap">
  <h2>Search frost dates by city</h2>
  <p class="small">
    Search by city, province/state, or country. City names link to local planting-date pages with crop-specific timing.  If you don't see your city listed here, try using your <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">zip or postal code to find frost dates</a>

  </p>
  <label class="sr-only" for="frost-city-search">Search frost dates by city</label>
  <input
    id="frost-city-search"
    type="search"
    placeholder="Search city, province/state, or country..."
    autocomplete="off"
    style="width:100%;max-width:36rem;margin:0.75rem 0 1rem;padding:0.75rem 0.9rem;border:1px solid #d8e2d0;border-radius:999px;"
  />
  <p class="small" id="frost-city-search-count" aria-live="polite">
    Showing {{ frostDateReference.cityRecords.length }} cities.
  </p>
  <table id="frost-city-table">
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>City</th>
        <th>Region</th>
        <th>Country</th>
        <th>Last spring frost</th>
        <th>First fall frost</th>
        <th>Frost-free days</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {% for row in frostDateReference.cityRecords %}
        <tr data-search="{{ row.cityName | lower }} {{ row.regionName | lower }} {{ row.regionAbbr | lower }} {{ row.countryLabel | lower }}">
          <td><strong><a href="{{ row.cityUrl }}">{{ row.cityName }}</a></strong></td>
          <td>{{ row.regionName }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.countryLabel }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.lastFrostLabel }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.firstFrostLabel }}</td>
          <td>{{ row.frostFreeDays }}</td>
        </tr>
      {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to use frost dates</h2>
  <p>
    Frost dates are best used as planning signals. The last spring frost helps estimate when frost-sensitive crops such as tomatoes, peppers, basil, cucumbers, squash, beans, corn, and melons can usually move outdoors.
    The first fall frost helps estimate whether a crop has enough time to mature before cold weather returns.
  </p>
  <ul class="tight">
    <li><strong>Last spring frost</strong> — the average date after which spring frost risk usually drops.</li>
    <li><strong>First fall frost</strong> — the average date when fall frost risk begins returning.</li>
    <li><strong>Frost-free days</strong> — the approximate number of days between those two dates.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A longer frost-free season gives warm-season crops more room to mature. A shorter season usually means earlier varieties, indoor starts, row cover, or more conservative crop choices matter more.
    For a visual comparison of Canadian city seasons, see the <a href="/data/canada-garden-climate-atlas/">Canada Garden Climate Atlas</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card leaderboardCallout">
  <h2>What frost-free days do and do not tell you</h2>
  <p>
    Frost-free days are useful for comparing season length, but they do not tell the whole story. Two cities can have similar frost-free windows but very different summer heat.
    For heat-loving crops, compare this table with <a href="/data/growing-degree-days-by-city/">Growing Degree Days by City</a>.
    For a ranked view of the tightest seasons, see <a href="/data/rankings/cities-with-the-shortest-growing-seasons/">Cities With the Shortest Growing Seasons</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Before planting tender crops</h2>
  <p>
    Always check the actual forecast before setting tender plants outdoors. Averages are helpful for planning, but a late cold snap can still happen after the average last frost date.
    If your site is exposed, low-lying, windy, or outside town, it may run colder than the city average.
  </p>
</section>

<script>
(function () {
  const input = document.getElementById("frost-city-search");
  const table = document.getElementById("frost-city-table");
  const count = document.getElementById("frost-city-search-count");
  if (!input || !table || !count) return;
  const rows = Array.from(table.querySelectorAll("tbody tr"));
  function update() {
    const query = input.value.trim().toLowerCase();
    let visible = 0;
    rows.forEach((row) => {
      const matches = !query || (row.dataset.search || "").includes(query);
      row.hidden = !matches;
      if (matches) visible += 1;
    });
    count.textContent = `Showing ${visible} ${visible === 1 ? "city" : "cities"}.`;
  }
  input.addEventListener("input", update);
}());
</script>
